  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Deborah Weston comments on family and friends. She called on Elizabeth Moorfield and the Parkers for a visit. She criticizes the behavior of Mary S. Parker. Deborah wrote: &quot;I disliked her more than I ever did before. I am included to think that she begins to feel that she must manage the Soc[iety] herself.&quot; Sylvia Ammidon &quot;holds fast her integrity.&quot; She relates an incident involving Parker and Edmund Quincy, who &quot;particularly spoke of sinful ministers.&quot; Deborah read the first volume of Lord Edward and admired it. [The Lord Edward referred to is: The Life and Death of Lord Edward Fitzgerald, by Thomas Moore.] Deborah comments: &quot;What a pity that Tom Moore is such a reprobate.&quot; She blames &quot;those lying tory histories&quot; for certain misconceptions.</subfield>
